05172nam a22007095i 9781400883813DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20162007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008838137 a10.1515/97814008838132doi  a(DE-B1597)474348  a(OCoLC)979954591  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHV8599.A4bL39 2008eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a956.7044/32221 aLazreg, Marnia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTorture and the Twilight of Empire :bFrom Algiers to Baghdad /cMarnia Lazreg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHuman Rights and Crimes against Humanity ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Imperial Politics and Torture -- tChapter 1. Revolutionary-War Theory -- tChapter 2. Militarization of the Colonial State -- tChapter 3. Psychological Action -- tChapter 4. Models of Pacification: From Nietzsche to Sun Tzu -- tPart II: Ethnography of Torture -- tChapter 5. Doing Torture -- tChapter 6. Women: Between Torture and Military Feminism -- tPart III: Ideology of Torture -- tChapter 7. Conscience, Imperial Identity, and Torture -- tChapter 8. The Christian Church and Antisubversive War -- tChapter 9. Fanon, Sartre, and Camus -- tPart IV: Reflections on Torture -- tChapter 10. Moralizing Torture -- tChapter 11 Repetitions: From Algiers to Baghdad -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences and Selected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTorture and the Twilight of Empire looks at the intimate relationship between torture and colonial domination through a close examination of the French army's coercive tactics during the Algerian war from 1954 to 1962. By tracing the psychological, cultural, and political meanings of torture at the end of the French empire, Marnia Lazreg also sheds new light on the United States and its recourse to torture in Iraq and Afghanistan. This book is nothing less than an anatomy of torture--its methods, justifications, functions, and consequences. Drawing extensively from archives, confessions by former torturers, interviews with former soldiers, and war diaries, as well as writings by Jean-Paul Sartre, Albert Camus, and others, Lazreg argues that occupying nations justify their systematic use of torture as a regrettable but necessary means of saving Western civilization from those who challenge their rule. She shows how torture was central to guerre révolutionnaire, a French theory of modern warfare that called for total war against the subject population and which informed a pacification strategy founded on brutal psychological techniques borrowed from totalitarian movements. Lazreg seeks to understand torture's impact on the Algerian population--especially women--and also on the French troops who became their torturers. She explores the roles Christianity and Islam played in rationalizing these acts, and the ways in which torture became not only routine but even acceptable. Written by a preeminent historical sociologist, Torture and the Twilight of Empire holds particularly disturbing lessons for us today as we carry out the War on Terror.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xAtrocities. 0aTorturezAlgeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTorture. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140088381340uhttps://www.degru